          "improving_parameter": "Object-generated harmful factors (#31)",
          "worsening_parameter": "Productivity (#39)"
        },
        "inventive_principles": [
          "#18 Mechanical vibration",
          "#28 Mechanics substitution",
          "#35 Parameter changes"
        ],
        "reasoning_chain": "1) Faster print speeds exacerbate vibration and noise. 2) Improve #31, worsen #39. 3) Matrix (31,39) → {28, 35, 10, 19}. 4) Apply #28 Mechanics substitution: switch from Cartesian bed-slinger to CoreXY gantry — only the lightweight toolhead moves, eliminating massive Y-axis bed mass that amplifies vibration. 5) Apply #35 Parameter change: replace standard stepper drivers with silent-step drivers (TMC2208 stealthChop algorithm) that use sine-wave current interpolation, eliminating 80% of motor whine. 6) Apply #18 Vibration (convert): input-shaping (Klipper resonance compensation) generates an inverse-vibration pulse that pre-cancels ringing artefacts, allowing higher acceleration without ghosting. 7) Result: <40 dB(A) operation, print speed +60%.",
        "solution": "High-speed silent FDM platform: CoreXY motion system + TMC2208 stealthChop drivers + input-shaping resonance compensation (ADXL345 accelerometer auto-calibrates). Acoustic level drops from 62 to 38 dB(A); achievable print speed increases from 60 to 150 mm/s with equal quality. Enclosed with acoustic foam panels if <35 dB(A) required.",
        "complexity": "medium"
      },
      {
        "id": "TG-30",
        "source": "TRIZ-GPT / smart grid (peak demand management)",
        "language": "en",
        "domain": "energy/electronics",
        "problem": "Peak electricity demand (typically 5–8 PM) overloads the distribution grid, requiring expensive peaking plants that run only a few hundred hours per year and still risk brownouts.",
        "contradiction_pair": {
          "improving_parameter": "Productivity (#39)",
          "worsening_parameter": "Loss of energy (#22)"
        },
        "inventive_principles": [
          "#19 Periodic action",
          "#23 Feedback",
          "#25 Self-service"
        ],
        "reasoning_chain": "1) Peaking plants are wasteful and expensive; building more capacity is inefficient. 2) Improve #39 (grid supply sufficiency), worsen #22 (energy wasted in peaking plants). 3) Matrix (39,22) → {19, 23, 35, 25}. 4) Apply #19 Periodic: shift flexible loads (EV charging, HVAC pre-cooling, dishwashers) to off-peak periods via automated scheduling. 5) Apply #23 Feedback: real-time grid-frequency signal (±0.1 Hz from 50/60 Hz) propagated to smart appliances as a broadcast demand signal — no central controller needed. 6) Apply #25 Self-service: appliances autonomously decide to defer or advance their load based on the frequency signal. 7) 15–20% peak demand reduction demonstrated in national trials (UK Power Networks).",
        "solution": "Frequency-responsive demand management: smart EV chargers, heat pumps, and HVAC units read grid frequency; 49.9 Hz triggers deferral, 50.1 Hz triggers advance. Aggregated across a city, 200 MW of flexible load shifts automatically. No central communication; self-organising response. Combined with V2G discharge from EV fleet at peak, peak demand reduced 18%.",
        "complexity": "medium"
      },
      {
        "id": "MOD-11",
        "source": "TRIZ in construction engineering (underwater concrete placement)",
        "language": "en",
        "domain": "civil/manufacturing",
        "problem": "Placing concrete in submerged or flowing water environments causes cement washout and aggregate segregation, producing weak, non-uniform concrete in underwater foundations and cofferdams.",
        "contradiction_pair": {
          "improving_parameter": "Stability of object's composition (#13)",
          "worsening_parameter": "Productivity (#39)"
        },
        "inventive_principles": [
          "#35 Parameter changes",
          "#24 Intermediary/Mediator",
          "#10 Preliminary action"
        ],
        "reasoning_chain": "1) Water flowing through fresh concrete disperses cement; preventing dispersion requires admixtures that slow placement. 2) Improve #13, worsen #39. 3) Matrix (13,39) → {35, 10, 24, 1}. 4) Apply #24 Mediator: submerged tremie pipe acts as an intermediary — concrete enters from below the existing pour surface, displacing water upward rather than falling through it. 5) Apply #35 Parameter change: anti-washout admixtures (HPMC-based viscosity modifier) raise viscosity 20-fold, preventing dispersion even at 1 m/s current. 6) Apply #10 Preliminary action: pre-fill the tremie with a cement grout plug to prevent water ingress before concrete pumping starts. 7) Result: underwater concrete achieves 85% of in-air 28-day strength.",
        "solution": "Tremie-pipe underwater concrete placement: 200–300 mm steel tremie pipe primed with cement grout plug; anti-washout HPMC admixed concrete flows continuously from the bottom up, always maintained in contact with the fresh pour face below water surface. Meets EN 206 class XA2 and ACI 304R requirements for underwater placement.",
        "complexity": "medium"
      },
      {
        "id": "MOD-12",
        "source": "TRIZ in energy technology (tandem solar cell efficiency)",
        "language": "en",
        "domain": "energy/materials",
        "problem": "Single-junction silicon photovoltaic cells are limited to ~29% theoretical efficiency (Shockley-Queisser); higher efficiency multi-junction cells are 10× more expensive and require exotic III-V substrates.",
        "contradiction_pair": {
          "improving_parameter": "Loss of energy (#22)",
          "worsening_parameter": "Manufacturability (#32)"
        },
        "inventive_principles": [
          "#1 Segmentation",
          "#3 Local quality",
          "#17 Transition to another dimension"
        ],
        "reasoning_chain": "1) More junctions = higher efficiency but exponentially higher cost. 2) Improve #22, worsen #32. 3) Matrix (22,32) → {1, 17, 35, 10}. 4) Apply #1 Segmentation: divide the solar spectrum into sub-bands, each harvested by a different material — perovskite top cell (1.68 eV bandgap, absorbs UV/visible) + silicon bottom cell (1.1 eV, absorbs NIR). 5) Apply #17 Transition to another dimension: stack the two cells in a vertical tandem — light passes through the top cell and residual is absorbed by the bottom cell. 6) Apply #3 Local quality: each sub-cell optimised for its spectral band. 7) Two-terminal perovskite/Si tandem avoids III-V cost; lab record 33.9% efficiency (LONGi, 2023); manufacturing cost only 20% above PERC.",
        "solution": "Perovskite/Silicon monolithic tandem cell: methylammonium-free (Cs,FA)Pb(I,Br)₃ perovskite top cell (1.68 eV) deposited by slot-die coating on n-type TOPCon silicon bottom cell; recombination junction via indium tin oxide interlayer. Certified 33.9% PCE (LONGi 2023); compatible with existing silicon cell manufacturing with one extra deposition step.",
        "complexity": "complex"
      },
