        "reasoning_chain": "1) More sensitive microphone = more ambient noise. 2) Improve #28, worsen #36. 3) Matrix (28,36) → {26, 32, 28, 2}. 4) Apply #28 Mechanics substitution: replace passive acoustics with dual-microphone electronics. 5) Apply #22 Convert harm: the second reference microphone records ambient noise without body contact; digital subtraction removes it from the chest-contact signal. 6) Apply #23 Feedback: real-time adaptive filter updates coefficients every 5 ms to track changing ambient noise. 7) Net: body sound SNR improved by 30 dB in 90 dB ambient environments; output amplified 40× and frequency-shaped for heart/lung emphasis.",
        "solution": "Adaptive noise-cancelling electronic stethoscope: two MEMS microphones — one in the chest piece (body + ambient), one on external housing (ambient only); ANC DSP computes inverse ambient signal and subtracts in real time. SNR gain: +30 dB. Bluetooth transmission to smartphone app for waveform display and AI-assisted murmur classification.",
        "complexity": "medium"
      },
      {
        "id": "MOD-14",
        "source": "TRIZ in environmental engineering (direct air carbon capture)",
        "language": "en",
        "domain": "environmental/chemical",
        "problem": "Direct Air Capture (DAC) of CO₂ requires moving large air volumes through sorbent beds using powered fans; energy cost (2,000–2,500 kWh/tonne CO₂) makes deployment economically unviable at required climate scale.",
        "contradiction_pair": {
          "improving_parameter": "Loss of substance (#23)",
          "worsening_parameter": "Loss of energy (#22)"
