        "reasoning_chain": "1) DAC needs fans = energy; without fans = low contact area = slow capture. 2) Improve #23 (capture CO₂), worsen #22 (energy). 3) Matrix (23,22) → {25, 35, 22, 2}. 4) Apply #22 Convert harm: use existing wind as the motive force — passive wind-driven DAC contactors (louvred towers) exploit natural convective and wind flows to circulate air through sorbent. 5) Apply #25 Self-service: calcium looping sorbent regenerates via the same waste heat stream from co-located industrial process. 6) Apply #35 Parameter change: use anion exchange resin that captures CO₂ from humid air and releases it upon humidity swing (moisture-swing, zero thermal energy). 7) Combined energy: <800 kWh/tonne CO₂.",
        "solution": "Passive moisture-swing DAC: anion-exchange resin (quaternary ammonium hydroxide on polystyrene) captures CO₂ from ambient air when dry; releases pure CO₂ when wetted with water vapour — no heat, no fans. Wind-driven louvred towers provide air contact. Regeneration energy: 0 kWh heat + <200 kWh electrical/tonne CO₂. Scales via modular towers sited at coastal/humid locations.",
        "complexity": "complex"
      },
      {
        "id": "MOD-15",
        "source": "TRIZ in civil engineering (bridge cable vibration fatigue)",
        "language": "en",
        "domain": "civil/transportation",
        "problem": "Stay cables on cable-stayed bridges undergo rain-wind induced vibration at large amplitudes, causing fatigue at anchorage zones and deteriorating cable sheathing; passive viscous dampers are effective but must be replaced on a 10–15 year cycle.",
